Crucially: **Nowhere in the function is `p.destroy()`, `p.destroyForcibly()`, `p.waitFor()`, or any other process-release method called.** The only release operation present is `in.close()` (line 29), which closes the *input stream*, not the `Process`. Closing streams does *not* release the underlying process — the `Process` remains alive and becomes a zombie/leaked resource unless `destroy()` or `waitFor()` is called.

Also note:
- `p` is never passed as an argument to any other method (no interprocedural calls involving `p`).
- `p` is never returned.
- `p` is local, never assigned to a field or shared alias beyond `p`.
- There is no `finally` block that calls `p.destroy()` or similar.
